<subSubSection id="C3666572831BFFEF1CDE397E2FEEE668" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC336F9831BFFF01CDE397E2845E460" blockId="14.[151,1437,1776,2002]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1436,152,458]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="16" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Description: 
<typeStatus id="54C7885B831BFFF11D7E397E2CD9E250" box="[358,467,1816,1842]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Holotype</typeStatus>
male: Head: Eyes bare. Frons narrow, narrowing from level of anterior ocellus to its anterior margin, at narrowest point approximately one quarter eye width, matt black, dulled with microsculpture, frontal and interfrontal setulae very short, a few longer ones present along the anterior margin. Orbital plates without setulae, brightly shining black. Lunule bearing two setulae, orange-brown in ground colour, covered with silver dusting. Parafacials and upper face also silvered. Anterior genal setulae in a single row of four or five along mouth margin, none of these especially strong. Antennal flagellomere just over twice as long as deep, entirely black apart from being obscurely brown ventrally basally on inner surface. Arista yellow basally, long plumose, plumosity at its greatest extent almost twice depth of antennal flagellomere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336F9831AFFF01CDE3F7629B4E4A8" blockId="15.[151,1436,152,458]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Thorax: Disc shining, bearing short setulae at most one quarter length of orbital setae. Anepisternum with three strong setae anteriorly and three posteriorly. Katepisternum with two setulae, anterior one significantly weaker and shorter than posterior. One propleural and one finer stigmatical setae. Scutellum slightly damaged, brightly shining on the disc, apparently with no setulae between the strong setae. Squamae whitish with a white fringe. Wings clear with light brown veins. Wing length 3.0mm. Legs entirely black.</paragraph>
<caption id="DF036671831AFFF01C8F394B281EE2E9" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" startId="15.[151,269,1837,1861]" targetBox="[243,1340,511,1788]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph id="8BC336F9831AFFF01C8F394B281EE2E9" blockId="15.[151,1437,1837,1931]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis id="B908EAEB831AFFF01C8F394B2C6AE227" bold="true" box="[151,352,1837,1861]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">FIGURES 29–34.</emphasis>
Male terminalia of: 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D7A831AFFF01E5739482FE6E227" authority="Introduction &amp; Fallén &amp; Morge, 2007" authorityName="Introduction &amp; Fallén &amp; Morge" authorityYear="2007" box="[591,748,1838,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Silba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="botanica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B908EAEB831AFFF01E5739482FE6E227" box="[591,748,1838,1861]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Silba botanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23B5790831AFFF01EED39482E41E227" box="[757,843,1838,1861]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
29. epandrium and associated structures, lateral view. (showing position of surstylar teeth on inner surface). 30. aedeagus lateral view. 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D7A831AFFF0181E393429DFE20B" authority="Introduction &amp; Fallén &amp; Morge, 2007" authorityName="Introduction &amp; Fallén &amp; Morge" authorityYear="2007" box="[1030,1237,1874,1897]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Silba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviplumosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B908EAEB831AFFF0181E393429DFE20B" box="[1030,1237,1874,1897]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Silba breviplumosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23B5790831AFFF018C53937283BE20A" box="[1245,1329,1873,1896]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
31. epandrium and associated structures, lateral view. 32. ventral view. 33. posterior view. 34. aedeagus lateral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BC336F98305FFEF1CDE3EFE2C8BE490" blockId="16.[151,1436,152,978]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Male terminalia; 
<figureCitation id="13472A7C8305FFEF1D873EFE2F46E5D0" box="[415,588,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="15.[151,269,1837,1861]" captionTargetBox="[243,1340,511,1788]" captionTargetId="figure-195@15.[223,1363,495,1809]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Male terminalia of: Silba botanica sp. nov. 29. epandrium and associated structures, lateral view. (showing position of surstylar teeth on inner surface). 30. aedeagus lateral view. Silba breviplumosa sp. nov. 31. epandrium and associated structures, lateral view. 32. ventral view. 33. posterior view. 34. aedeagus lateral view." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Figs. 29 &amp; 30</figureCitation>
. In lateral view epandrium almost twice as high as s wide, posteriorly rather pointed and culminating in a short process, anteriorly relatively broad and square ended, semi-circular excavation on dorsal margin, ventral margin with a row of short setulae along most of its length, a few setulae dorsally near the posterior apex. Cerci very small, not sclerotised, bearing a row of short setulae along dorsal margin. Surstyli almost completely enclosed within epandrium apart from a small, rounded anterior projection on the inner surface, with a continuous row of fourteen small teeth lying parallel to the ventral margin, the most posterior of these projecting posteriorly beyond shell of epandrium. Aedeagus with basal part relatively broad with a semi-circular excavation dorsally, outer portion long and narrow, half way along with a 45° bend, apex slightly flared.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC336F98305FFEF1CDE3C662FEEE668" blockId="16.[151,1436,152,978]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Differential diagnosis: This species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D7A8305FFEF1F3E3C662980E778" authority="McAlpine, 1956" authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="1956" box="[806,1162,512,538]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Silba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abstata">
<emphasis id="B908EAEB8305FFEF1F3E3C662ECBE77B" box="[806,961,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Silba abstata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B088305FFEF1FD23C662980E778" author="McAlpine, J. F." box="[970,1162,512,538]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="521 - 544" refId="ref18526" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1956) Old World lonchaeids of the genus Silba Macquart (= Carpolonchaea Bezzi), with descriptions of six new species (Diptera: Lonchaeidae). Canadian Entomologist, 88, 521 - 544." type="journal article" year="1956">McAlpine, 1956</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
group of species all of which are rather small, with a relatively short antennal flagellomere, an elongate epandrium with short cerci and with a row of teeth on the inner surface of the surstyli situated parallel to the ventral margin. McAlpine (1975) provided a key to the known species. With a pale squamal fringe and a simple aedeagus this species is most closely similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D7A8305FFEF1DB13CC62FF9E7D8" authority="(de Meijere, 1910)" baseAuthorityName="de Meijere" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[425,755,672,698]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Silba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucens">
<emphasis id="B908EAEB8305FFEF1DB13CC62F1BE7DB" box="[425,529,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">S. lucens</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B088305FFEF1E393CC62FE1E7D8" author="de Meijere, J. C. H." box="[545,747,672,698]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="115 - 120" refId="ref18709" refString="de Meijere, J. C. H. (1910) Studien uber sudostasiatische Dipteren II. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie, 51, 115 - 120." type="journal article" year="1910">de Meijere, 1910</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from Java and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7C4D7A8305FFEF1FB13CC629EBE7D8" authority="McAlpine, 1964" authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="1964" box="[937,1249,672,698]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Silba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitata">
<emphasis id="B908EAEB8305FFEF1FB13CC62913E7DB" box="[937,1049,672,697]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">S. imitata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFED4B088305FFEF18393CC629EBE7D8" author="McAlpine, J. F." box="[1057,1249,672,698]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="661 - 757" refId="ref18570" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1964) Descriptions of new Lonchaeidae (Diptera). Canadian Entomologist, 96, 661 - 757." type="journal article" year="1964">McAlpine, 1964</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F36B76698305FFEF19313CC62892E7D8" box="[1321,1432,672,698]" name="Australia" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Australia</collectingCountry>
. It is distinguished from both these species by having more teeth on the surstylus including one projecting posteriorly and by the more slender, angled aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
